	<div class="posts">
	<a name="111596352290243172"></a>
    
    <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-08-31 -->
    
    TiddlyWiki: Ohmygosh, I'm in Love.  
    
    </font></h2>
    
    
    <p>
	<p><a href="http://tiddlywiki.com/">TiddlyWiki - a reusable non-linear personal web notebook</a>.&nbsp; <a href="http://www.sauria.com/blog/2005/05/11#1299">Ted Leung</a> just altered my life.&nbsp; What have I been craving, praying for, putting off, and living miserably without he just ushered into my hands, along with a dose of <a href="http://shared.snapgrid.com/gtd_tiddlywiki.html">GTD the TiddlyWiki Way</a> too. &ldquo;All your tasks are belong to you&rdquo; indeed.</p><p>Here it is, a micro-content blog/wiki/hyper-thingie and my very favorite list of requirements:</p><ul><li>Completely Dis-intermediated &ndash; it runs in a web page anywhere a browser can use it</li><li>Completely lightweight &ndash; HTML, CSS, and JavaScript &ndash; the whole thing is built in a single&nbsp;web page; There&rsquo;s even Wiki on a [USB] Stick.&nbsp; Criminetlies.</li><li>Pure Web information model: no database engines, no server requirement, permanent publishable formats. Is it REST, is it AJAX? &nbsp;I dunno but I&rsquo;m gonna love it.</li><li>My favorite open-source license: BSD &ndash; essential for operating in mixed company without guilt</li><li>The only &ldquo;platform-dependence&rdquo; seems to be the ability to have a hierarchical file/URL system and an appropriately-standards-compliant browser.&nbsp; </li><li>There is a server-side version, and I really need to find out about that.</li><ul><li>One, <a href="http://phiffer.org/tiddly/">TiddlyWikiRemote</a>, publishes to a server-side&nbsp;into an RSS feed!</li><li>Aasted Sorenson&rsquo;s <a href="http://aasted.org/wiki/">MyWiki experiment</a> does server side into a file, and provides user login</li><li><a href="http://poul.staugaard.dk/IeWiki.htm">IEWiki</a> is bent&nbsp;to be&nbsp;specific to&nbsp;Internet Explorer and it lives&nbsp;as a Windows .hta file on a local machine &ndash; verrrry interessssting.</li></ul><li>It&rsquo;s kinda purty too.&nbsp; Cool way of showing history.&nbsp; Tastes great. Less filling.</li></ul><p>OK Ted, here&rsquo;s the deal.&nbsp; I know cats are a problem and Vicki would really like to spend time with Julie and the kids so how about <em>we bring</em> <em>dinner</em> <em>to you?&nbsp; </em>We love Bainbridge Island anyhow.&nbsp; I figure August.&nbsp; I owe you, guy.</p><p>I shall now lapse into a fit of weeping incoherence.&nbsp; Ah, be there baby.&nbsp; Be there for poppa. Make my dreams come true.&nbsp; OK, deep breath. Right click&nbsp;for download, right?</p><p align="center"><small><em>I wonder how it works with WebDAV or, dare I speak the incantation, FrontPage Extensions?<br />Could this be a way of operating my content off of a CD-ROM without installing or preempting a local web server?<br />Be still my pulse-throbbing brain ...</em></small></p>
    </p>
	<span class="byline">posted by orcmid
       at <a href="http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2005/05/tiddlywiki-ohmygosh-im-in-love.asp">5/12/2005 10:52:02 PM</a>,
