	<div class="posts">
	<a name="111594563150011832"></a>
    
    <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-08-31 -->
    
    3I: Individualized Interactive Instruction
    
    </font></h2>
    
    
    <p>
	<p><a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2005-7/0511w.html#item11">ACM News Service: Innovative Instruction</a>.&nbsp; A program for real-time interaction between professors and students, connected by wireless in the classroom, is being hailed as a way of altering the reluctance of students to ask and answer questions.&nbsp; In the blurb, it is difficult to tell whether anonymity is crucial to the technique or not.</p><p>From the account in Daniel Miller&rsquo;s 2005-05-10 <a href="http://www.dailybruin.ucla.edu/news/articles.asp?id=33254"><em>Daily Bruin</em> article</a>, it seems very clear that, how much I think learning to interact without self-consciousness is an important student skill, including willingness to make mistakes, that&rsquo;s not how things work in reality.&nbsp; And the use of an anonymous forum, at least in &ldquo;town hall&rdquo; settings, not only works to elicit participation, but there is serious engagement and participation.</p><p>The article does not provide any clue about the nature of 3I other than it is an open-source package similar to the Educational Testing Service&rsquo;s expensive&nbsp;<a href="http://www.ets.org/discourse/">Discourse</a> package.&nbsp; Greater provision for customization is claimed for 3I.</p><p>In <a href="http://www.college.ucla.edu/edtech/interviews/kaiser.htm">an interview</a> on use of technology as a tool for achieving teaching goals, Electrical Engineering Professor <a href="http://www.ee.ucla.edu/faculty/bios/kaiser.htm">William J. Kaiser</a> explains how valuable the opening up of student feedback is for his own assessment of how the material is landing and what may need to be put in to convey a concept he wants to enliven and impart to the students. It is about closing gaps &ldquo;between what the students understand and the instructor&rsquo;s perception of that comprehension.&rdquo;</p><p>Here&rsquo;s the dynamic that pleases Kaiser:</p><blockquote><p>&ldquo;We refer to the protocol as individualized, interactive instruction (3I). This method is still based on an instructor teaching&mdash;because that&rsquo;s very, very good for students &mdash;we just add a networked component so that communication with the lecturer becomes a two-way street. It works in the following manner: I, as an instructor, present material. I then present a problem that all the students can see, via the interface, on their personal&nbsp;<strong>wireless notebook </strong>screens. They then begin solving a problem, and I&rsquo;m able to see the responses, in real time, of every student&mdash;every keystroke that&rsquo;s entered is revealed. I don&rsquo;t know which student is providing which response; from my perspective, they&rsquo;re simply a list of numbers and this preserves the anonymous nature.</p><p>&ldquo;It provides an incredible degree of insight. As students respond to a problem, I&rsquo;m able to see characteristic errors that the entire class is making, and <a name="immediate feedback">&nbsp;</a><strong> I can review material to address a particular weakness </strong>. I&rsquo;ve found that in typically just one problem cycle of about 10 minutes, a given weakness can be completely eliminated. In a typical 3I session, I&rsquo;ll work through 6 different problem types, starting from very simple to very complex. At the beginning, students might have only two-thirds success on the initial problem, and at the end of the session, virtually all students are solving the hardest problem.&rdquo;</p></blockquote><p>I would love to find out exactly what this program does, but I can&rsquo;t find it anywhere.&nbsp; For free, open-source software, it is remarkably well hidden.&nbsp; (I did find <a href="http://sourceforge.net/projects/d3e/">D3E</a> though, and I am holding onto that link so I don't lose it one more time [;&lt;).</p>
    </p>
	<span class="byline">posted by orcmid
